      "question": "Why are long-distance dependencies hard for recurrent networks to model?",
      "stem_format": "plain_text",
      "choices_format": "plain_text",
      "choices": [
        "Because distant words can only influence each other through many sequential recurrent steps",
        "Because RNNs cannot represent verbs and nouns in the same state space",
        "Because LSTMs require fixed-length inputs",
        "Because recurrence removes all contextual information"
      ],
      "answer_index": 0,
      "explanation": "In an RNN, information must be passed along one step at a time. When related words are far apart, their interaction path becomes long, which makes learning the dependency harder.",
